Introduction¶

For the last couple of labs and home work sessions in the class, we have had chance to analyze New York City, San Francisco, and Toronto data. I am working with my sister to finalize her move to Atlanta, US. And during her move to the US, we are mainly interested in find a nice and safe neighborhood for her to stay at.

Thus, in this project, we will analyze venues and crime data Atlanta. We will try to find the best place to live in Atlanta based on safety and our interest.

The use of this analysis can be expand to anyone who is interested in moving to Atlanta.

Data Description¶

Atalanta Crime Data¶

The Atlanta PD provides listing of all type of crimes by Neighborhood Planning Units (NPUs) and Neighborhood, along with its coordinate. NPUs are neighborhood-scale governmental structure used in the city of Atlanta. There are 25 NPUs in Atlanta, lettered from A-Z (except Q). The coordinate will be used to merge with Foursquare API data to determine the nearby venues associated with a crime. The data provided by Atlanta PD spans from 2009 to 2020. For simplicity and completeness of data, we will only use data for full year 2019.

The data can be downloaded from: https://www.atlantapd.org/i-want-to/crime-data-downloads

Example of the data can be seen below:

VERSION = '20200101' # Foursquare API version

radius = 500 # define radius
def getNearbyVenues(group_names, location_col_name, latitudes, longitudes, limit, radius=500):
    
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(group_names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(name)
            
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            limit)
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  location_col_name+' Latitude', 
                  location_col_name+' Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

Neighborhood coordinate¶

Since we can't reliably and easily get neighborhood longitude and latitude from any of the website or data source. We will use a work around from our crime database. First, we will find the centroids of all crime points by neighborhood in our data frame. This will give us a rough estimate of the center point of that neighborhood.

Normally to find the centroid for a collection of longitudes and latitude is actually a little bit more complicated than simply averaging longtitude and latitude. This is because the as we approach and cross the intermedian or the poles, the longitude and latitude change their sign to signify the change in coordinates. For example -179 longitude and 179 longitude points are actually very close to each other. However, the average for those 2 longitude is 0, which is halfway across the world.

However, since all of our neighborhood is based in Atlanta, so the points for each neighborhood is not too far apart, and most importantly, Atlanta doesn't spread through the intermedian, or is anywhere close to the poles. Thus, we will examine the dataframe to see the range of longitude and latitude given. If there is no sign changed, we can treat all points in the dataframe as a flat database and simply use the arithmetic mean to find the centroid. This can easily be done by seeing the std and min max of longitude and latitude.

If we detect a change in coordinates signs, we will choose a different method in finding the centroid. The most accurate method I found online would be to utilize the center of gravity method. To perform this method, we convert longitude and latitude into Cartesian (x,y,z) coordinates. The average x, y and z coordinate is calculated. This average coordinate lies within the interior of the earth and is the true center of mass, and a line can be drawn from the center of the earth passing through this point then out to the surface of the earth which is the geographic midpoint. The average x, y and z coordinate is converted into the latitude and longitude for the midpoint.

You can find more information about calculating geographic mid point here or here to calculate the geographic midpoint.

Let's check the range of lat and lon in our dataframe.

def most_common(row, start_index, top_num):
    """Function to return the most X numbers by categories
    start_index is the index of columns where your categories begin.
    """
    row_categories = row.iloc[start_index:]
    row_categories_sorted = row_categories.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    return row_categories_sorted.index.values[0:top_num]

Next, since we are narrowing down neighborhoods to find a place to live, let's concentrate on narrowing down based on its safety. We will use K-Means to clusters our neighborhood based on their crime count.

Clustering Neighborhood Based on Crime Using K-means.¶

To determine the best k for our KMeans algorithm, we will use the elbow method. We define the following:

  • Distortion: It is calculated as the average of the squared distances from the cluster centers of the respective clusters. Typically, the Euclidean distance metric is used.
  • Inertia: It is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.

We will iterate the value of k from 2 to 10 and calculate the values of distortions for each value of k and calculate the distortion and inertia for each value of k in the given range.

# import k-means from clustering stage
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn import metrics 
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist 

def find_k(df):
    """Function to graph distortions and inertials by k."""
    distortions = [] 
    inertias = [] 
    mapping1 = {} 
    mapping2 = {} 
    k_values = range(2,20)


    for k in k_values: 
        #Building and fitting the model 
        kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(df) 

        distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_, 
                          'euclidean'),axis=1)) / df.shape[0]) 
        inertias.append(kmeanModel.inertia_) 

        mapping1[k] = sum(np.min(cdist(df, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_, 
                     'euclidean'),axis=1)) / df.shape[0] 
        mapping2[k] = kmeanModel.inertia_ 

    # Plot Distortion and Inertial to find the optimal k
    fig,(ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (16,4))

    ax1.plot(k_values, distortions, 'bx-') 
    ax1.set_xlabel('Values of K') 
    ax1.set_xticks(list(range(2,20)))
    ax1.set_ylabel('Distortion')
    ax1.grid(axis='x')
    ax1.set_title('The Elbow Method using Distortion')

    ax2.plot(k_values, inertias, 'rx-') 
    ax2.set_xlabel('Values of K') 
    ax2.set_xticks(list(range(2,20)))
    ax2.set_ylabel('Inertia') 
    ax2.grid(axis='x')
    ax2.set_title('The Elbow Method using Inertia') 

    plt.show()
    
# Plot
find_k(alt_crime_norm.iloc[:,3:alt_crime_norm.shape[1]])

import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.colors as colors

def map_clusters_alt(df,cluster_label,cluster_no):
    # create map
    map_clusters = folium.Map(location=[latitude, longitude], zoom_start=11)

    # set color scheme for the clusters
    x = np.arange(cluster_no)
    ys = [i + x + (i*x)**2 for i in range(cluster_no)]
    colors_array = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(ys)))
    rainbow = [colors.rgb2hex(i) for i in colors_array]

    # add markers to the map
    markers_colors = []
    for lat, lon, poi, cluster in zip(df['Latitude'], 
                                      df['Longitude'], 
                                      df['Neighborhood'], 
                                      df[cluster_label]):
        label = folium.Popup(str(poi) + ' Cluster ' + str(cluster), parse_html=True)
        folium.CircleMarker(
            [lat, lon],
            radius=5,
            popup=label,
            color=rainbow[cluster-1],
            fill=True,
            fill_color=rainbow[cluster-1],
            fill_opacity=0.7).add_to(map_clusters)

    return(map_clusters)

Looking at the summary table, we can see that cluster 3 is our most dangerous clusters, with manslaughter and homicide very high. Follow by cluster 2 and 4, depends on what we are looking for. Since we want to have a safe environment, we will be picking neighborhoods from cluster 1 and 0 only. Let's try to run k-means again to see if we can further narrow down cluster 1, since they have quite a bit of neighborhoods. We will normalize data inside cluster 1 again, to have a better view of their neighborhoods.

Looking at the summary, we can see that for our purposes, we should can pick cluster 0 to begin looking for a place to live.

However, let's try putting some weight on the features first since we have different priorities. We want to be closer to Vietnames and Asian restaurants, and groceries the most, we will give them a squared weight. For gym and park, let's put 2. For the rest of the categories except Other, let's give them a weight of 1.5.

Using Weight with K-means¶

So the result doesn't change much with the weight. Let's try to use DBScan to see if we get any better than 11 neighborhoods. The idea when using DBScan is that it will classify all of the faraway points as outliers, and we will only have like-wise neighborhoods.

Discussion¶

Due to time constraints and my limited knowledge of Atlanta database, not all methods were exhausted. Also, our crime analysis would be much improved if we can also include demographic data of Atlanta, like income level, population, area size so we can use crime rate, and number of venues/1000 citizen for example. That would make the analysis much richer.

Observations¶

In this exercise, we have run multiple clustering iterations to find the best place to live for a Vietnamese food lover. We found 4 main neighborhoods to start looking at, and 7 reserve neighborhoos. And our best place to live in probably inside inner Atlanta, but not near downtown or midtown Atlanta.

Our 4 best places to live are:

  • Ardmore
  • Brookwood Hills
  • Collier Hills
  • Collier Hills North

Failing to find a proper housing situation, we can always find more places to live in:

  • Channing Valley
  • Englewood Manor
  • Georgia Tech
  • Just Us
  • Pleasant Hill
  • State Facility
  • Whitewater Creek

Conclusion¶

In this exercise, we have successfully find 11 neighborhoods that are safe, and interesting (based on our own preference) to live in. Please keep in mind that when we are analyzing the safetiness of a neighborhood, due to lack of population data, we have to rely on the absolute value of the crime counts. This might not be representative of satefy and crime rate, since different neighborhoods have different population size and area.

While the analysis was promising, we can always further refine the analysis by bringing in demographic and population data, as well as things that might heavily affect our happiness like traffic and housing prices data.
